President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 2016 as National Child Abuse Prevention Month in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of preventing child abuse and neglect and providing a safe and nurturing environment for all children. It highlights the alarming number of children who are neglected or abused each year and the lasting consequences it can have on their lives. The proclamation calls for a collective effort from individuals, communities, and the government to intervene and prevent child abuse. It also emphasizes the need for strong support systems and resources for families facing these challenges. The proclamation concludes with a call to observe the month with programs and activities that promote child abuse prevention and meet the needs of children.